Binding

This course will principally look at the binding between ‘macromolecules’ and ‘ligands’.

This might be":

  • biological macromoleules (such as proteins, DNA…)
  • synthetic macromolecules (such as porphyrins, crown ethers…)

Binding

Binding is an equilibrium process

The binding of a macromolecule (blue, hard left) to a ligand (orange, center) to form a complex (right) is a equilibrium process.

We know that this equilibrium can be ‘forced’ into one form or another by changing the concentration of one of the species.

Binding

The binding depends on factors such as:

  • sterics between ligand and macromolecule
  • complementary charges
  • complementary hydrogen bonding
  • complementary non-polar regions
  • …

but more simply, it can be modelled mathematically.

Revision of fundamentals of thermodynamics

My first year thermodynamics course.

Entropy, \((\Delta) S\)

Internal energy \((\Delta)U\)

Enthalpy, \((\Delta) H\)

Gibbs’ free energy \((\Delta) G\) (constant pressure systems)

Helmholtz’ free energy \((\Delta) A\) (constant volume systems)

Most things we care about in thermodynamics are state functions .

Gibbs’ free energy

The entropy of the surroundings in a closed system is related to the enthalpy of the system, such that:

\(\Delta S_{\textrm{sur}} = -\frac{\Delta H_\textrm{sys}}{T}\)

Gibb’s then restated the second law of thermodynamics into a single equation considering the system and surroundings:

\(\Delta G = \Delta H - T \Delta S\)

Helmholtz’ free energy

There is of course a constant volume equivalent that works in the same way, the Helmholtz free energy:

\(\Delta S_{\textrm{sur}} = -\frac{\Delta U_\textrm{sys}}{T}\)

\(\Delta A = \Delta U - T \Delta S\)

Spontenaity

The spontaneity of a reaction at different temperatures.

Spontanaity

The temperature dependence of Gibbs free energy for different reaction types: endothermic and increase in entropy (top left), endothermic with a decrease in entropy (top right), exothermic with an increase in entropy (bottom left) and exothermic with a decrease in entropy (bottom right).

Equilibrium

For the equilibrium:

\(A+B \leftrightharpoons AB\)

Then the equilibrium constant K is given by:

\(K = \frac{[AB]}{[A][B]}\)*

*(assuming the solution is ‘ideal’ or the concentration can be used as an approximation for the activity)

Van’t Hoff linked this ‘driving force’ of the reaction to the equilibrium constant, K.

\(\Delta H - T\Delta S = -RT \ln K\)

Temperature dependence of equilibrium

\(\ln K= -\frac{\Delta H}{R}\frac{1}{T} + \frac{\Delta S}{R}\)

A plot of ln K against 1/T has a gradient of −ΔH/R and an intercept of ΔS/R (assuming ΔH and ΔS are linear over the range studied.

Thermodynamics of binding

For the equilibrium between ‘receptor’, ‘\(R\)’, and ‘ligand’, ‘\(L\)’ forms complex [\(R\bullet L\)]:

\(R + L \rightleftharpoons R \bullet L\)

with the equilibrium constant of binding, \(K_b\) given by:

\(K_b = \frac{[R \bullet L]}{[R][L]}\)

this is sometimes expressed as the dissociation constant of the complex, \(K_d\):

\(K_d = \frac{[R][L]}{[R \bullet L]}\)

Chemical Thermodynamics in Context

We will apply this very basic set of thermodynamic equations in this course to:

  • develop mathematical models of binding
  • understand the thermodynamics behind a range of intermolecular interactions
